      {
        "paragraph_index": 1,
        "text": "### Key Findings\n\n- **Two dissociation steps** are confirmed (H₂L → HL⁻ → L²⁻), consistent with oxalic acid being a dicarboxylic acid.\n- **pKa₁ = −1.2** — This is unusually low (strongly acidic), meaning the first proton is released almost completely even in moderately acidic solutions. This reflects the strong electron-withdrawing effect of the adjacent carbonyl group.\n- **pKa₂ = 3.8** — The second dissociation is much weaker, as the negatively charged HL⁻ intermediate resists losing another proton.\n- The large gap (~5 pKa units) between the two steps is characteristic of dicarboxylic acids where the two carboxylate groups are adjacent (α-position), maximizing inductive destabilization of the dianion.\n\n> **Source:** NIST SRD-46 (ligand_8872, metal_68/H⁺), measured at 25 °C, I = 0.1 M (aqueous), with 56 total VLM entries across both steps.",
